@startuml 04-device-revocation-key-rotation
title Device Revocation Flow

skinparam backgroundColor #FEFEFE
skinparam roundcorner 10
skinparam shadowing false

skinparam sequence {
    ArrowColor #D32F2F
    LifeLineBorderColor #D32F2F
    ParticipantBackgroundColor #FFEBEE
    ParticipantBorderColor #D32F2F
}

actor "User\n(Trusted Device)" as user
participant "Trusted Device\nExtension" as trusted
participant "S3" as s3
participant "Revoked Device\nExtension" as revoked

== Step 1: Initiate Revocation ==

user -> trusted : Select device to revoke
trusted -> trusted : Confirm user identity\n(require unlock)
trusted -> trusted : Load current vault

note right of trusted
    **Why Rotate Vault Key?**
    Revoked device may have
    cached the old Vault Key.
    New key = can't decrypt
    future vaults.
end note

== Step 2: Key Rotation ==

trusted -> trusted : Generate NEW Vault Key\n(256-bit random)

trusted -> trusted : Re-encrypt vault data\nwith NEW Vault Key
note right of trusted
    - New random IV
    - Same plaintext
    - New ciphertext
end note

== Step 3: Re-create Key Slots ==

trusted -> trusted : Remove revoked device's\nkey slot

trusted -> trusted : Create new key slots\nfor remaining devices
note right of trusted
    **For each trusted device:**
    1. Get device's ECDH public key
    2. Generate new ephemeral keypair
    3. ECDH -> ConcatKDF -> new KEK
    4. AES-GCM wrap NEW Vault Key

    **For master backup:**
    1. PBKDF2 from password
    2. AES-GCM wrap NEW Vault Key
end note

loop For each remaining device
    trusted -> trusted : Create ECDH key slot\nwith NEW Vault Key
end

trusted -> trusted : Create master backup slot\nwith NEW Vault Key

== Step 4: Commit Changes ==

trusted -> trusted : Increment revision
trusted -> trusted : Update timestamp
trusted -> trusted : Sign envelope (Ed25519)

trusted -> s3 : Upload new vault
s3 --> trusted : 200 OK

trusted --> user : Device revoked

== Step 5: Revoked Device Attempts Access ==

revoked -> s3 : Download vault
s3 --> revoked : New envelope

revoked -> revoked : Look for own key slot
revoked -> revoked : KEY SLOT NOT FOUND!

revoked -> revoked : Try cached Vault Key\n(if any)
revoked -> revoked : DECRYPTION FAILS!\n(wrong key)

note right of revoked
    **Revoked device cannot:**
    - Find its key slot (removed)
    - Decrypt with old Vault Key
      (data encrypted with new key)
    - Forge signatures
      (lacks valid device key)
end note

revoked --> revoked : Access denied

legend right
    **Revocation Guarantees:**
    - Forward secrecy: new key protects future data
    - Old data: was already accessible (can't revoke past)
    - Signature validation: revoked device can't sign valid envelopes
endlegend

@enduml
